WEBVTT

00:03.372 --> 00:31.287
When we entered

00:03.372 --> 00:31.287
the space program in the essentially early days of 
NASA's development, what differences do you see

00:03.372 --> 00:31.287
between then and now in terms of NASA's ideology 
and purpose? Well, the actual purpose of NASA

00:33.308 --> 00:38.415
really hasn't changed. It's a research and 
development organization, and as you may be

00:38.435 --> 01:01.088
aware, it grew out of the NACA, or NACA, which is the 
National Aeronautics Council, something

00:38.435 --> 01:01.088
that transitioned from NACA to NASA was 
occasioned by the Space Act of 1958, which in turn

01:01.979 --> 01:13.178
was at least in part triggered by the success of the 
Soviet space program. And from that time on,

01:13.198 --> 01:23.937
basically NASA has undertaken in the space arena 
to advance the state of technology and science,

01:24.406 --> 01:37.920
and to carry out the mission for the space missions 
that have been deemed most appropriate by the

01:24.406 --> 01:37.920
President and other administrations including 
the Congress. And of course we, following

01:37.940 --> 01:51.274
President Kennedy's commitment to put a man on the 
moon before the end of the decade of the 60s,

01:37.940 --> 01:51.274
put the bulk of our resources into that effort. And 
then following the successful conclusion of

01:52.250 --> 02:12.317
that, it had become obviously obvious to a lot of 
people within NASA and presumably many people in

01:52.250 --> 02:12.317
the government that the throwaway spacecraft is 
an extravagant luxury and we needed to work on

01:52.250 --> 02:12.317
something that would be reusable many times, in 
turn has evolved into the Shuttle Spacecraft

02:13.090 --> 02:21.662
System, which is more appropriately known as the 
National Space Transportation System. And by

02:22.943 --> 02:40.667
extension, following the realization that the 
Shuttle would in fact be successful, Mr. Reagan

02:22.943 --> 02:40.667
wanted us to concentrate on more immediate 
practical applications of the Shuttle for a year

02:22.943 --> 02:40.667
or two, which was done. And now we've embarked on 
building a permanent unmanned space station to be

02:41.002 --> 02:50.034
operational before the end of the decade. It 
started in 84, I think, before 94 came out.

02:56.643 --> 03:05.575
When NASA was created under Eisenhower in 58, was 
it intended to be a civilian type of organization,

02:56.643 --> 03:05.575
even though its first members were primary 
military? Well, it was chartered. who would

03:08.474 --> 03:23.871
handle the civilian space program of the U.S. And I 
would take issue with your statement that the

03:08.474 --> 03:23.871
first members of the military, because the bulk of 
the agency was and always has been civilian. If you

03:23.891 --> 03:30.518
look at the Project Mercury astronauts, these 
basically were all military. There were only

03:30.538 --> 03:34.482
seven people out of several thousand in the 
agency. And, of course, all of the folks that had

03:35.288 --> 03:51.052
been working for NACA in the aeronautical field, 
that is the airfoil designers, the engine people,

03:35.288 --> 03:51.052
the ones that build and operate the wind tunnels 
and things of that sort, came along with the

03:35.288 --> 03:51.052
agency. And the unmanned space program also grew 
up within NASA, and this was when we were totally

03:51.072 --> 04:00.986
surveying. We probed to Jupiter and Mars, to 
Venus, things like that. So really there's only a

04:06.375 --> 04:18.590
very small percentage of military and those that 
are military working with NASA are basically

04:06.375 --> 04:18.590
following the civilian pursuers in their 
uniform. Do you think that the sexual revolution

04:18.610 --> 04:29.943
of the 70s and the civil rights movement of the 60s 
have affected the attitude of NASA and the

04:18.610 --> 04:29.943
entrance of the minorities into the space 
program? Well, I guess you'd have to say that to the

04:33.592 --> 05:03.531
extent that these things have affected the 
sociology of the United States in general, they

04:33.592 --> 05:03.531
have also affected the sociology of NASA 
specifically, we are finding that

04:33.592 --> 05:03.531
we can now obtain, for example, in the minority, 
racial minority category, racial minorities

04:33.592 --> 05:03.531
that have gained flight training and test pilot 
experience in the military, and are available to

05:04.017 --> 05:18.660
enter into the NASA program were back in the early 
60s, there were not such people anywhere in the

05:04.017 --> 05:18.660
military or in the U.S. social structure. We were 
also finding quite a number of women engineers,

05:18.680 --> 05:32.421
scientists, medical doctors, things of this 
sort, and you're starting to see women as pilots in

05:18.680 --> 05:32.421
the armed forces and flying for the commercial 
airlines. And I would imagine that before too many

05:37.582 --> 05:44.910
years are out, like, we'll have some selected 
pilot category within NASA also. Can you check

05:44.930 --> 05:47.893
this real quick? Yeah, I think that will work. Were 
women and minorities brought in gradually, or as

05:51.837 --> 06:01.007
you said, since there weren't too many in the 60s, 
was there a sudden push to bring them in? There was

06:02.371 --> 06:10.098
not a sudden push, but by the same token, they 
weren't brought in gradually either.

06:15.564 --> 06:30.758
I came into the program in 66, and there was one 
selection of 11 scientists in 67, and we got a few of

06:15.564 --> 06:30.758
the NOL, the Mandorbin Laboratory guys, when 
their program was canceled. But basically,

06:33.909 --> 06:46.541
between 1967 and 1978, 11 years, there were no new 
inputs into the astronaut corps. And what

06:46.561 --> 06:58.552
happened in 1978, we selected a total of 30 people, 
as they would call it, including six women and

06:46.561 --> 06:58.552
several racial minorities. And in the 
intervening 11 years, the

07:01.585 --> 07:09.356
texture of our social fabric had changed quite a 
bit. And additionally, we were looking at

07:09.376 --> 07:29.145
selecting people specifically in career 
patterns, i.e., as mission specialists, having

07:09.376 --> 07:29.145
created that billet, and looking at a spacecraft 
which was big enough to carry more than just the two

07:09.376 --> 07:29.145
or three that were required to fly it, We recently 
completed a Mission 7 on board, the 41G mission,

07:29.868 --> 07:39.637
and there's one Schedule 8 on board about a year 
from now. So you're getting to the point where you

07:40.378 --> 07:48.065
can afford to have a lot of differentiation in 
terms of duties and experience. It just seemed

07:48.825 --> 07:55.091
that's the way the situation fell out. In what ways 
do you think that women and minorities have added

07:55.111 --> 07:58.474
or maybe subtracted from the NASA program? Well, I 
think probably the biggest way that they've added

08:01.816 --> 08:13.689
is just by showing the American people that we've 
got a real cross-section of the population

08:01.816 --> 08:13.689
involved. You can't help but feel that you're 
getting more support from areas representing

08:13.709 --> 08:27.364
racial minorities and women's groups and things 
of this sort, and they see one of their own up there.

08:28.205 --> 08:30.488
participating and doing a good job. As you're 
probably aware, a tremendous demand for talks by

08:31.149 --> 08:41.401
and interviews with Sally Ride and some of the 
other folks. In fact, that's a bit of a personal

08:42.883 --> 08:56.279
hardship on her, and she's been relieved that Judy 
Resnick and some of the other folks wouldn't have

08:42.883 --> 08:56.279
gotten up to help share the load. Oh, that's good. I 
think it may also be interesting to look back and

08:59.812 --> 09:11.947
you note that the Soviets were the first to put a 
woman in space, Valentina Tereshkova. They made

09:11.967 --> 09:20.138
sure that she was up there by herself, but the 
technology basically was a one-person capsule at

09:11.967 --> 09:20.138
the time. And until we announced in, it must have 
been March of 82, When Sally arrived with me going

09:27.655 --> 09:36.405
up on a space shuttle flight, they had absolutely 
no interest discernible in having any more women

09:27.655 --> 09:36.405
in space. Immediately

09:36.545 --> 09:49.300
after Sally was selected and announced, we 
started getting questions along the lines of, why

09:36.545 --> 09:49.300
do you want to put a woman into space? We've already 
done it once. And so basically the implication

09:50.902 --> 09:54.346
being that was all that mattered. And what are her 
qualifications? What's she going to do up there?

09:59.787 --> 10:24.072
And then there was a long silence, and in

09:59.787 --> 10:24.072
August of 82, that is about five months later, 
during the Unispace conference in Austria, they

09:59.787 --> 10:24.072
had arranged to have a TV downlink to the 
conference, and all of a sudden they announced, by

09:59.787 --> 10:24.072
the way, Svetlana Savitskaya, for the glory of 
Mother Russia, and all that sort of thing, is the a

10:24.490 --> 10:32.318
crew member in the current Soyuz crew going up to 
the Soyuz would have a Beamer message down to the

10:24.490 --> 10:32.318
assembled delegates. So they were very anxious 
that the United States might be perceived as

10:33.639 --> 10:42.648
affording greater opportunities to humankind 
than they were. And then again this spring, when it

10:43.649 --> 10:52.438
was, I don't know, I guess it was about a year ago 
when it was announced that the Soyuz was going up

10:43.649 --> 10:52.438
again, Kathy Charlton would be performing in the 
spacewalk, the EVA. We didn't hear anything from

10:57.809 --> 11:23.151
them, but you notice about July of this year, they 
made a point of sending Svetlana Savitskaya up a

10:57.809 --> 11:23.151
second time, thereby getting the title of the 
first woman to go into space twice, and they sent

10:57.809 --> 11:23.151
her outside on the spacewalk, just so they could 
claim that the first spacewalk by a woman was done

